<p>Curtis's suicide "made for instant myth", in music critic <a href="/wiki/Simon_Reynolds" title="Simon Reynolds">Simon Reynolds</a>'s words.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45" title=""><span>[</span>46<span>]</span></a></sup> Jon Savage wrote in his obituary for Curtis in <i>Melody Maker</i>, "Now no one will remember what his work with Joy Division was like when he was alive; it will be perceived as tragic rather than courageous."<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46" title=""><span>[</span>47<span>]</span></a></sup> In June 1980, the posthumous single "<a href="/wiki/Love_Will_Tear_Us_Apart" title="Love Will Tear Us Apart">Love Will Tear Us Apart</a>" was released, which hit number thirteen on the British singles chart.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47" title=""><span>[</span>48<span>]</span></a></sup> In July 1980, <i>Closer</i> finally came out, peaking at number six on the British album chart.<sup id="cite_ref-mojo1994_3-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mojo1994-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> <i>NME</i> reviewer Charles Shaar Murray wrote, "<i>Closer</i> is as magnificent a memorial (for 'Joy Division' as much as for Ian Curtis) as any post-<a href="/wiki/Elvis_Presley" title="Elvis Presley">Presley</a> popular musician could have."<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48" title=""><span>[</span>49<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The members of Joy Division had made a pact long before Curtis's death that, should any member leave, the remaining members would change the name of the group.<sup id="cite_ref-Silence_41-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Silence-41" title=""><span>[</span>42<span>]</span></a></sup> Eventually renaming themselves <a href="/wiki/New_Order" title="New Order">New Order</a>, the band was reborn as a three-piece with Sumner assuming vocal duties; the group later recruited Morris's girlfriend <a href="/wiki/Gillian_Gilbert" title="Gillian Gilbert">Gillian Gilbert</a> to round out the lineup as keyboardist and second guitarist. New Order's first single, the 1981 release "<a href="/wiki/Ceremony_(song)" title="Ceremony (song)">Ceremony</a>", featured the last two songs written with Ian Curtis.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49" title=""><span>[</span>50<span>]</span></a></sup> While the group struggled in its early years to escape the shadow of Joy Division, New Order eventually went on to much greater commercial success than their predecessor band.</p>
<p>Further Joy Division material has been released since the band's demise. <i><a href="/wiki/Still_(Joy_Division_album)" title="Still (Joy Division album)">Still</a></i>, a compilation of live tracks and rare recordings, was issued in 1981. Factory put out the <i><a href="/wiki/Substance_(Joy_Division_album)" title="Substance (Joy Division album)">Substance</a></i> compilation in 1988, which included several out-of-print singles.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50" title=""><span>[</span>51<span>]</span></a></sup> Another compilation, <i><a href="/wiki/Permanent_(album)" title="Permanent (album)">Permanent</a></i>, was released in 1995 by <a href="/wiki/London_Records" title="London Records">London Records</a>, which had acquired the Joy Division catalogue after Factory Records went bankrupt in 1992. A comprehensive box set, <i><a href="/wiki/Heart_and_Soul_(album)" title="Heart and Soul (album)">Heart and Soul</a></i>, came out in 1997.</p>
<p><a name="Musical_style" id="Musical_style"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Joy_Division&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Musical style">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Musical style</span></h2>
<table class="metadata plainlinks mbox-small" style="border:1px solid #aaa; background-color:#f9f9f9;">
<tr>
<td class="mbox-image">
<div class="center">
<div class="floatnone"><a href="/wiki/File:Gnome-speakernotes.svg" class="image" title="Gnome-speakernotes.svg"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/94/Gnome-speakernotes.svg/50px-Gnome-speakernotes.svg.png" width="50" height="50" border="0" /></a></div>
</div>
</td>
<td class="mbox-text" style="line-height:1.1em;">
<table style="width:100%; background:transparent; border-collapse:collapse; padding:0; margin:0;">
<tr>
<td style="padding:2px 0;"><a href="/wiki/File:Joy_Division_She%27s_Lost_Control.ogg" title="File:Joy Division She's Lost Control.ogg">"She's Lost Control"</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
